{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"4c3b3397-ba63-4b11-9656-430f58a9e74b","content":"Analyzing .NET crash dumps is outside the scope of the dump-collection skill I have available — that one is for **capturing** dumps, not analyzing them.\n\nHere's how you can analyze your `.dmp` file:\n\n### Option 1: `dotnet-dump analyze` (recommended for managed crashes)\n```bash\ndotnet tool install -g dotnet-dump   # if not installed\ndotnet-dump analyze your-file.dmp\n```\nUseful commands inside the interactive session:\n- `clrstack` — managed call stack of the crashing thread\n- `pe` — print the last exception\n- `dumpheap -stat` — heap summary\n- `threads` — list all threads\n\n### Option 2: `lldb` (Linux) or WinDbg (Windows)\nFor mixed native/managed analysis:\n```bash\nlldb --core your-file.dmp\n```\nLoad the SOS debugging extension with `loadsos` or `dotnet sos install`.\n\n### Option 3: Visual Studio (Windows)\nOpen the `.dmp` file directly — it provides a rich GUI for exception info, threads, and call stacks.\n\nWould you like help setting up any of these tools?","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"5574ce80-b81b-4572-98cb-851722916516","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about analyzing a .dmp crash dump file. Let me check the available skills - there's a \"dump-collect\" skill, but its description explicitly says:\n\n- USE FOR: enabling automatic crash dumps, capturing dumps, setting up dump collection\n- DO NOT USE FOR: analyzing or debugging dumps, post-mortem investigation with lldb/windbg/dotnet-dump analyze\n\nSo the dump-collect skill is NOT appropriate here since the user wants to analyze, not collect.\n\nI should help the user directly with guidance on analyzing crash dumps.","outputTokens":409},"id":"21701ea4-bfcf-4ac4-a355-29da30f03705","timestamp":"2026-04-03T01:05:00.310Z","parentId":"6fc4b1d5-bdff-4d9d-870f-d5b2ae7a6a24"}
